<DOC><DOCNO> AP891205-0107 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-PX-12-05-89 1424EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-CityEmployment     12-05 0121</FIRST><SECOND>AM-City Employment,100</SECOND><HEAD>City Employment Sets Record</HEAD><HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's cities employed a record2,570,103 workers as of October 1988, the Census Bureau saidTuesday.   That is 28,735 more employees than worked for cities a yearearlier and about 9,000 more than the previous record, set in 1980.   Payrolls for city employees totaled about $5 billion, up 6.2percent from 1987, with full-time employees averaging $2,270 amonth.   While the bureau counted 19,200 municipal governments, 58percent of employees worked for the 270 cities with populations of75,000 or more.   Police accounted for the largest single category of cityemployees, at 399,822, followed by education, 333,325; localutilities, 227,170, and fire protection, 196,977.</TEXT></DOC>